I’m not even sure how to begin to unpack what the last couple of months have been for Cam. And maybe, once I’ve processed my frustration and healed my hurt, when the anger has abated and the fear has stopped sitting on my throat, I’ll be able to share what I’ve learned, what’s happened, the battles I’ve fought, the ways I’ve grieved. I know there is power in the sharing. 

For in the sharing we foster connection, in the connection we build acceptance, in the acceptance, love is born. 

I’m grateful for those in my family and in my community—near and far, here and elsewhere—who understand the importance and necessity of acceptance. It is everything. Cam’s success depends on it. 

Also, side note…

That boy LOVES pizza. 🥰😁😉

I am learning to look BEHIND me, to measure my successes based on where I started and how far I’ve come, rather than looking AHEAD at the bridges I have yet to cross and how far I  have to go. How far WE have to go. 

*His language development was extremely delayed.
*I knew very little about autism and where to go and what to do for help.
*He melted down and cried everyday in preschool.
*He hit and pushed other children and required medication to curb aggression.
*We weren’t sure he’d be potty trained in time for first grade.
*We took noise cancelling headphones with us everywhere.
*He shut down most afternoons in first grade and his teacher once told me she went home from work with a headache everyday, thanks to him. 
*He needed private occupational and speech therapy.
*His therapist, Mr. Matt, worked with him for months on his behavioral and social challenges. 

And while his seventh grade year continues to be a painful mountain to climb, I look at where I’ve been and what I’ve learned and how far I’ve come and it makes me think that maybe, like my “sister of old,” Esther, I was “born for such a time as this.”

Some days I don’t want to feel that, to know that as deeply as I do. Some days I get angry or scared. Some days I am just so incredibly sad. But then, like a Disneyland ride line that wanders and weaves back and forth, back and forth, I eventually “get there,” to that place in my heart that reminds me that this was never a solo job. It’s a partnership. It’s an agreement he and I made together; a pact before life, a promise that will open fully to me in death. We’re in this together. Hand in hand. Side by side. 

I can keep doing it, simply because I know how far, how far, how gloriously far we’ve come.

My dermatologist is a delightful guy. He’s younger than me (which is totally weird), loves John Denver (also totally weird 😜), and looks like Jim Caviezel (which I find a bit dreamy). 

While lying in his awkward, reclining, dermatologist chair, waiting for the face injection that, let’s be honest, should have been Botox, he said, “So, how are things going?”

My immediate, going-through-the-motions-of-politeness response was, “Good! Good!”

And as the words left my mouth, it was as if I saw a bright, neon light in my mind, flashing, “Liar! Liar! Liar!”

But don’t we do that, my friends? Stay on the surface in our conversations with others sometimes? Maybe because it’s too painful or too uncomfortable to go deeper? To be vulnerable? Isn’t it easier to just say, “Good,” and move on? But just because it’s easy, does that make it best? What happens when we start getting real?

“Actually,” I frantically blurted out, “I’m not good! I lied! My parents have left to serve an LDS mission and it feels like time is standing still and I’ve been crying a lot, like all the time, and I had no idea it was going to be like this and I’m just trying to figure it out and be brave and I’m so tired and I worry about if they’re healthy and what they’re eating and and and…”

What happens when we start getting real? Something beautiful happens.

That young, John Denver-lovin’ dermatologist sat and listened to me and was *there* for me. Present. Patient. Compassionate. He handed me a tissue and reassured me that it would be okay and that I’d “figure this out.” 

“It may take some time, even months, but it’s going to be okay,” he said. “It will. It will be okay.”

Cont’d in comments…

I have been learning more about awe; studying it in those small moments of “free time” that flit in and out of my life. 

“Experiencing more awe is associated with living healthier and more meaningful lives. A 2021 study reported that feeling more awe is correlated with reporting feeling lowered levels of daily stress. Intriguingly, people who feel more awe also tend to have lower levels of inflammatory cytokines.

Positive experiences of awe have also been found to increase feelings of well-being, life satisfaction and sense of meaning.

By becoming less attuned to ourselves and more attuned to the rest of the world, awe helps us re-contextualize ourselves.”

Paul Piff, an associate professor of psychological science at the University of California at Irvine says, “Awe helps make you feel like there’s more going on in the world than just you. And it gives you that sense of being a part of something much bigger than yourself.” ❤️ 

Awe-mazing!

I wonder what it would have been like for Isaac Behunin when he chose to settle the land along the Virgin River. I envy him the quiet solitude of exploring waterfalls and hidden canyons without the roar of shuttles transporting thousands of people across his beloved land. His focus would have been presence, not people; survival, not souvenir sales.

I can’t even begin to imagine the state of reverential awe he would have experienced with each sunrise, with each opportunity to watch golden light dance from those massive red facades. It is no small wonder to me, then, that Isaac Behunin would name the area Zion Canyon. 

Zion:
A sanctuary or refuge.
Perfect.
Ideal.
A city of God.
A holy place.

Hoppy Easter, from some-bunny who loves you. (It’s me!)

When Leslie Jo (@saltlakehairdesign) asked me what I was looking for in a haircut, what I hoped to achieve, what I wanted in a new look, I gulped down my vulnerability, took a deep breath, and prayed the tears would stay nestled in my eyeballs.

“I want hair that reflects me and my personality. Something sassy and fun…”

What Leslie Jo couldn’t have possibly known is that beneath that answer lies an insecure 42 year old woman who has become keenly aware of the aging skin on her neck, the fine lines around her eyes, the added weight on her hips. The creeeeeak in the hips every morning, the low energy. The positive self-talk that attempts to deflect the negative self-talk: “You’ve never really been the ‘pretty girl…’ and that’s okay! Because you are a hoot!”

Oye!

Such a naked and exposed position we often put ourselves in when we slide our bums into a stylist’s chair. But Leslie Jo, in kindness and in confidence, said, “I know exactly what to do!” ❤️❤️❤️

And so here I am, my friends, posting my cheesy, post-shag-haircut selfie to admit I’m not entirely sure what the moral of the story is. That aging is hard? That we aren’t alone in feeling “not young enough” or “not pretty enough” or “not good enough?” That perhaps we should be a little more gentle with ourselves? (Because we ARE all the enoughs.) Maybe it’s about being willing to open ourselves up to taking risks (even if it’s hair) and how it can prove to be a really good thing? Maybe the moral is all of these things. 

Or maybe, it’s simply, never underestimate the power of a really good haircut. ❤️❤️❤️

When my parents left for their mission, it was my wonderful Aunt Cindy who encouraged me to keep a record of the miracles that would occur because of their service and sacrifice.

She said, “Leish, you will find the entire family will be blessed…just watch what happens and record each miracle and blessing that a family member receives while they are gone.” 

And my friends, I have been doing just that in this beautiful journal. 

I’ve been thinking a lot about miracles today, as I enter the final stretch on my beloved Angel Mother project. I have watched and been in awe as so many miracles have taken place in regards to this project. The miracle of touching a heart that is grieving. The miracle of coming together to serve as a community of women. The miracle of the recipient who feels seen and loved. The miracle of dollars stretched and donations given. The miracle of no matter how many women I attempt to serve there is always enough—enough money, enough help, enough product donation. And while there have been some setbacks and discouragements this year, I continue to cling to what I know: that miracles are real, that God is aware and good, that the way is always made for this to be a successful project, and that some miracles are just good people with kind hearts. ❤️

#angelmother #angelmotherproject #loveoneanother #bekindalways #mothersday2023 #charityneverfaileth

I met Marci at the beginning of the school year, when she commented on the earrings I was wearing. (They were probably giant birds, or flowers, or hot dog buns! 🤣)

“I love your earrings!…I wish I could pull them off the way you can!,” she said.

And that was when I set out to prove to her that she COULD, by gifting her a new pair of funky/fun/colorful/wild earrings every few weeks. It quickly became the most joy-invoking, giddiness-inducing, personal service project for me, and I loved it! Marci and I have shared a lot of laughs this past year. 

There are opportunities to serve all around us, my friends! I pray we “fine tune” our attention to them and then ACT…and spread a little joy. Today and always!

I remember a summer long ago, when James and I were dating and falling in love. He’d drive his old, white Chevy Blazer to the base of the mountains behind his parents’ home—past the road’s pavement and beyond the gravel, to a dead end. It was usually nighttime when he’d turn that Blazer around so we were facing the valley below us. 

From our high vantage point, we could see all the stoplights in the distance—tiny and bright, like a strand of Christmas tree lights—and we’d watch them change from green to yellow to red. There was something dreamy about those lights. We’d listen to Coldplay’s Parachutes album and make-out like fools.

Now, many years later, I look at the lights outside our home on a tepid summer night and can’t help but think there is something dreamy about them too. How much has changed, how much we’ve grown, how deep our lives together have become. And while the romance of the lights on a summer night and the quiet togetherness is still there, a sense of grounded security and comfortable loyalty is now there as well. It’s a remarkable feeling. 

Truly, summer is for lovers.❤️

I looked at the lens sitting in my lap as I waited for my dad to meet me and thought, “Yep. This could be a metaphor for my life.” 

I turned to Bridget, sitting beside me in the front seat of the car, and said, “When he gets here, I’m going to get out looking like this. It needs to be a funny memory of the last time he sees me in person for a year!” 

I was given an extraordinary gift this past week. The gift of spending time with my parents, who flew home from Croatia for some important family stuff. (Adoption finalization, an LDS temple sealing, a blessing of the sweetest chubby-cheeked babe.) Running to my mom in the airport, eating cookies beside the pool, playing Tenzi,  snuggling (ahem…harassing) my dad while he attempted to go to bed were just some of the highlights! What a beautiful week it was. 

But…

(And it’s a pretty big but!) 

The inevitable “good-bye” had to come. And it was almost as emotional and heart-wrenching as the first time. I kissed my dad and hugged my mom tight and cried and cried. 

I wasn’t more than ten minutes on the road back home when I realized I had left a dress at my parent’s house. My dad offered to meet me so I wouldn’t have to backtrack. He’s a good dad like that!

We took this picture together, shared another quick hug, and then I cried all the way through Sardine Canyon.

So here I am, dear ones, at what sort of feels like the beginning again. Forgive the analogy, but I liken it to AA! Ha ha! I started my “sobriety” on January 30th. At first it was incredibly painful and hard. Eventually I would learn how to navigate my new normal—crying less and focusing on the daily miracles more. 

Then…they came home and I fell right of the bandwagon! I drank them up and soaked them in, trying to stay completely present in their presence. Oh, what a joy to be in the same room and on the same couch as them once again! 

My sobriety begins again. I know it will hurt for a while but I also know I survived the last six months. I did it! I was brave. I was positive. I fought for joy and won it over. I can do it again. (Right…RIGHT?!) 

Hi! My name is Aleisha and it’s been three days since I last hugged my parents…

On rare occasions I’ll find them like this…laughing happily, talking and “playing nice” together. 

When I do, I always think: 1.) This is the good stuff of life! And 2.) I give them fifteen minutes before they try to kill each other! 🤣

“It is literally impossible to be a woman. You are so beautiful, and so smart, and it kills me that you don’t think you’re good enough. Like, we have to always be extraordinary, but somehow we’re always doing it wrong.

You have to be thin, but not too thin. And you can never say you want to be thin. You have to say you want to be healthy, but also you have to be thin. You have to have money, but you can’t ask for money because that’s crass. You have to be a boss, but you can’t be mean. You have to lead, but you can’t squash other people’s ideas. You’re supposed to love being a mother, but don’t talk about your kids all the damn time. You have to be a career woman, but also always be looking out for other people. You have to answer for men’s bad behavior, which is insane, but if you point that out, you’re accused of complaining.

You’re supposed to stay pretty for men, but not so pretty that you tempt them too much or that you threaten other women because you’re supposed to be a part of the sisterhood. But always stand out and always be grateful. But never forget that the system is rigged. So find a way to acknowledge that but also always be grateful. You have to never get old, never be rude, never show off, never be selfish, never fall down, never fail, never show fear, never get out of line. It’s too hard! It’s too contradictory and nobody gives you a medal or says thank you! And it turns out in fact that not only are you doing everything wrong, but also everything is your fault.

I’m just so tired of watching myself and every single other woman tie herself into knots so that people will like us.” 

We are not meant to tie knots when we were born to be rock stars! ❤️

Tonight I washed Cam’s most beloved blue blanket. As I pulled it out of the dryer—tattered and torn and raggedy-looking from years of love and use—I thought about how the blanket has been Cam’s comfort item, constant companion, and very best friend over the years. 

“He’s still my little boy,” I thought, as I gave the blanket a shake, “a little boy stuck in a young man’s body!”

When I took it to him he was already curled up in his bed, talking nervously about the first day of school and the thunderstorms we were expected to have in the morning. He took the blanket from my hands, plopped it onto the top of his head and said, “Now I feel much safer.” 😭

So tell me, how does a mama send an awkward boy too tall for his feet, too quirky for his peers to understand, with a voice that cracks into that terrible pit of eight grade? I know I have to let him go and grow and become a man, but how do I do that when he still greets me with a light of relief in his eye when he sees I have  his freshly washed blanket? 

The world is too cruel
And the middle school is too,
For such a boy as my Cam.❤️

(Prayers for my special needs mamas tonight. 🙏🏻)

It never ceases to amaze me what the mountains will teach us if we are open enough to listen and mindful enough to pay attention. 

1. Look for the light in the darkness and you’ll find it. When you do, cling to it. It will bring comfort. 
2. The sun will always rise and there is great hope in that. 
3. Friends and loved ones will help ease the burdens of life and bring joy to the (sometimes HARD) journey. 
4. It’s good to ground yourself when you feel scared. What do you see? What do you hear? Breathe deeply. (Singing “I Am a Child of God” helps.) 
5. Always remember that no one walks the path alone. Whatever that path may be…pain, illness, death, heartbreak. Life was never meant to be a solitary experience.
6. Celebrate the successes, relish the moments you prove yourself conqueror, ENJOY the view.

*A Solo Hiker’s Prayer*

Dear Lord,

Bless my ankles, that they may be sturdy, and my big toes, that they may avoid all the jutting rocks on the trail.

May all the murderers be in another town, convening for a murder convention, and not hiding out in the trees. 

May the bears be sleeping in an early hibernation, so as not to mistakenly see me as a McNugget Happy Meal. 

May my map app hold steady so that Search and Rescue is not dispatched because I’ve managed to wind up in Wyoming.

Bless the moose, that they may be as uninterested in me as I am in watching golf on TV. 

And lastly, thank you for the gift of my life. I! Am! Alive! Thank you for my body and for all it can do. And thank you for this gorgeous Mother Earth. I am so blessed. 

Oh! And my snacks! Thank you for my snacks.
Amen

They push me and pull me, they stretch me and try me. They cause frustration and pain and heartache and fear. They make me question my ability to parent and challenge what I thought I knew about the job in the first place. It. Is. Hard. 

But that is exactly how I grow. As if in the depth of exhaustion, they tuck their hands underneath my arms and lift me up and show me the way. To growth. To being a better version of myself. 

And that is why they teach me and excite me, they edify me and they awe me. They humble me. They make me laugh and they bring great joy into my life. They are my life’s greatest treasures. 

That’s called motherhood.

Initially, this sign gave me the giggles. With snow in the trees and a layer of ice on the boardwalk, there were no flowers to be found. Anywhere!

And isn’t that kind of like life!? We often find ourselves in the cold and icy pain of our challenges and grief, wondering where in the heck all the flowers have gone!!! We see nothing but snow and it feels bleak to our spirits. 

But what if, maybe, just maybe, beneath the surface—and if we dig a little deeper—we find a bloom or two hidden under there? 

This week, as a storm of melancholy and frustration has rolled into my heart space, I have had to make a more concerted effort to seek after the flowers; to *really* look for them hiding in the cold. They are the figurative gifts I’ve been given—health, a home, James, my children—and they have helped to bring an attitude of gratitude into my life.

Blooms are blessings and petals are promises from God that we won’t EVER be left alone.

The other night I watched a video of the beautiful Lily Gladstone giving a speech at Variety’s “Power of Women” event. I was struck by several poignant things she said. 

She shared a Northern Cheyenne saying: “A nation is not defeated until the hearts of its women are on the ground.” She then said, “So I know that it is our work {as women} to uplift each other.” So. Powerful. 

This online sphere of “pretty perfectionism” and “loathsome comparisons” would place us, women, like chess pieces on a game board meant only to checkmate Queen against Queen; us against each other. No one wins. Hearts fall. 

But one thing I know to be true is this: women need women. It’s as simple and as profoundly gorgeous as that. We have a divinely innate ability (a gift!) to champion, support, love, carry, and encourage one another. We have a responsibility to see ourselves in our sisters and to recognize that their joys and their sufferings aren’t so different from our joys and our sufferings. With this reflected recognition comes an increase in empathy, grace, and charity—attributes our wonderful and worrisome world needs more of. 

Sister, I see you.
Your heart is safe with me.
